ATT Server Attribute Settings

Settings that may be set on each attribute.

ATTS_SET_UUID_128ïƒ

Set if the UUID is 128 bits in length

ATTS_SET_WRITE_CBACKïƒ

Set if the group callback is executed when this attribute is written by a client device

ATTS_SET_READ_CBACKïƒ

Set if the group callback is executed when this attribute is read by a client device

ATTS_SET_VARIABLE_LENïƒ

Set if the attribute has a variable length

ATTS_SET_ALLOW_OFFSETïƒ

Set if writes are allowed with an offset

ATTS_SET_CCCïƒ

Set if the attribute is a client characteristic configuration descriptor

ATTS_SET_ALLOW_SIGNEDïƒ

Set if signed writes are allowed

ATTS_SET_REQ_SIGNEDïƒ

Set if signed writes are required if link is not encrypted

ATT Server Attribute Permissions

Permissions used to describe a attributeâ€™s security setting. These values can be set in any combination.

ATTS_PERMIT_READïƒ

Set if attribute can be read

ATTS_PERMIT_READ_AUTHïƒ

Set if attribute read requires authentication

ATTS_PERMIT_READ_AUTHORIZïƒ

Set if attribute read requires authorization

ATTS_PERMIT_READ_ENCïƒ

Set if attribute read requires encryption

ATTS_PERMIT_WRITEïƒ

Set if attribute can be written

ATTS_PERMIT_WRITE_AUTHïƒ

Set if attribute write requires authentication

ATTS_PERMIT_WRITE_AUTHORIZïƒ

Set if attribute write requires authorization

ATTS_PERMIT_WRITE_ENCïƒ

Set if attribute write requires encryption

ATT Client Discovery and Configuration Settings

Settings used to configurate ATT Discovery procedure for ATT Clients.

ATTC_SET_UUID_128ïƒ

Set if the UUID is 128 bits in length

ATTC_SET_REQUIREDïƒ

Set if characteristic must be discovered

ATTC_SET_DESCRIPTORïƒ

Set if this is a characteristic descriptor

ATT Client Awareness of Database Change

ATT Server Callbacks

typedef uint8_t (*attsReadCback_t)(dmConnId_t connId, uint16_t handle, uint8_t operation, uint16_t offset, attsAttr_t *pAttr)ïƒ

Attribute group read callback.

This is the attribute server read callback. It is executed on an attribute read operation if bitmask ATTS_SET_READ_CBACK is set in the settings field of the attribute structure. For a read operation, if the operation is successful the function must set pAttr->pValue to the data to be read. In addition, if the attribute is variable length then pAttr->pLen must be set as well.

Param connId:

DM connection ID.

Param handle:

Attribute handle.

Param operation:

Operation type.

Param offset:

Read data offset.

Param pAttr:

Pointer to attribute structure.

Return:

status of the operation. ATT_SUCCESS if successful.

typedef uint8_t (*attsWriteCback_t)(dmConnId_t connId, uint16_t handle, uint8_t operation, uint16_t offset, uint16_t len, uint8_t *pValue, attsAttr_t *pAttr)ïƒ

Attribute group write callback.

This is the attribute server write callback. It is executed on an attribute write operation if bitmask ATTS_SET_WRITE_CBACK is set in the settings field of the attribute structure.

Param connId:

DM connection ID.

Param handle:

Attribute handle.

Param operation:

Operation type.

Param offset:

Write data offset.

Param len:

Length of data to write.

Param pValue:

Pointer to data to write.

Param pAttr:

Pointer to attribute structure.

Return:

status of operation. ATT_SUCCESS if successful.

typedef uint8_t (*attsAuthorCback_t)(dmConnId_t connId, uint8_t permit, uint16_t handle)ïƒ

ATTS authorization callback type.

This callback function is executed when a read or write operation occurs and the security field of an attribute structure is set to ATTS_PERMIT_READ_AUTHORIZ or ATTS_PERMIT_WRITE_AUTHORIZ respectively.

Param connId:

DM Connection ID.

Param permit:

Set to ATTS_PERMIT_WRITE for a writre operation or ATTS_PERMIT_READ for a read operation.

Param handle:

Attribute handle.

Return:

status of the operation. ATT_SUCCESS if successful, else if failure the ATT_ERR_AUTH is typically returned.

typedef void (*attsCsfWriteCback_t)(dmConnId_t connId, uint8_t changeAwareState, uint8_t *pCsf)ïƒ

ATTS client supported features write callback type.

This callback function is executed when the client supported features record for this client has been updated.

Param connId:

DM Connection ID.

Param changeAwareState:

The state of awareness to a change, see ::attClientAwareStates.

Param pCsf:

Pointer to the client supported features value.

Return:

None.

typedef void (*attsCccCback_t)(attsCccEvt_t *pEvt)ïƒ

ATTS client characteristic configuration callback.

Client characteristic configuration callback. This function is executed when a CCCD value changes. This happens when a peer device writes a new value to the CCCD or when a CCCD table is initialized by calling AttsCccInitTable.

Param pEvt:

Pointer to callback structure.

Return:

None.

uint8_t AttcDiscServiceCmpl(attcDiscCb_t *pCb, attEvt_t *pMsg)ïƒ

This utility function processes a service discovery result. It should be called when an ATTC_FIND_BY_TYPE_VALUE_RSP callback event is received after service discovery is initiated by calling AttcDiscService().

Parameters:

  • pCb â€“ Pointer to discovery control block.

  • pMsg â€“ ATT callback event message.

Returns:

ATT_SUCCESS if successful otherwise error.

void AttcDiscCharStart(dmConnId_t connId, attcDiscCb_t *pCb)ïƒ

This utility function starts characteristic and characteristic descriptor discovery for a service on a peer device. The service must have been previously discovered by calling AttcDiscService() and AttcDiscServiceCmpl().

Parameters:

  • connId â€“ DM connection ID.

  • pCb â€“ Pointer to discovery control block.

Returns:

None.

uint8_t AttcDiscCharCmpl(attcDiscCb_t *pCb, attEvt_t *pMsg)ïƒ

This utility function processes a characteristic discovery result. It should be called when an ATTC_READ_BY_TYPE_RSP or ATTC_FIND_INFO_RSP callback event is received after characteristic discovery is initiated by calling AttcDiscCharStart().

Parameters:

  • pCb â€“ Pointer to discovery control block.

  • pMsg â€“ ATT callback event message.

Returns:

ATT_CONTINUING if successful and the discovery procedure is continuing. ATT_SUCCESS if the discovery procedure completed successfully. Otherwise the discovery procedure failed.

void AttcDiscIncSvcStart(dmConnId_t connId, attcDiscCb_t *pCb)ïƒ

This utility function starts service include discovery for a service on a peer device. The service must have been previously discovered by calling AttcDiscService() and AttcDiscServiceCmpl().

Parameters:

  • connId â€“ DM connection ID.

  • pCb â€“ Pointer to service discovery control block.

Returns:

None.

uint8_t AttcDiscIncSvcCmpl(attcDiscCb_t *pCb, attEvt_t *pMsg)ïƒ

This utility function processes a service include discovery result. It should be called when an ATTC_READ_BY_TYPE_RSP allback event is received after service include discovery is initiated by calling AttcDiscIncSvcStart().

Parameters:

  • pCb â€“ Pointer to service discovery control block.

  • pMsg â€“ ATT callback event message.

Returns:

ATT_CONTINUING if successful and discovery procedure is continuing. ATT_SUCCESS if discovery procedure completed successfully. Otherwise the discovery procedure failed.

uint8_t AttcDiscConfigStart(dmConnId_t connId, attcDiscCb_t *pCb)ïƒ

This utility function starts characteristic configuration for characteristics on a peer device. The characteristics must have been previously discovered by calling AttcDiscCharStart() and AttcDiscCharCmpl().

Parameters:

  • connId â€“ DM connection ID.

  • pCb â€“ Pointer to discovery control block.

Returns:

ATT_CONTINUING if successful and configuration procedure is continuing. ATT_SUCCESS if nothing to configure.

uint8_t AttcDiscConfigCmpl(dmConnId_t connId, attcDiscCb_t *pCb)ïƒ

This utility function initiates the next characteristic configuration procedure. It should be called when an ATTC_READ_RSP or ATTC_WRITE_RSP callback event is received after characteristic configuration is initiated by calling AttcDiscConfigStart().

Parameters:

  • connId â€“ DM connection ID.

  • pCb â€“ Pointer to discovery control block.

Returns:

ATT_CONTINUING if successful and configuration procedure is continuing. ATT_SUCCESS if configuration procedure completed successfully.

uint8_t AttcDiscConfigResume(dmConnId_t connId, attcDiscCb_t *pCb)ïƒ

This utility function resumes the characteristic configuration procedure. It can be called when an ATTC_READ_RSP or ATTC_WRITE_RSP callback event is received with failure status to attempt the read or write procedure again.

Parameters:

  • connId â€“ DM connection ID.

  • pCb â€“ Pointer to discovery control block.

Returns:

ATT_CONTINUING if successful and configuration procedure is continuing. ATT_SUCCESS if configuration procedure completed successfully.

ATT HCI Error Status

ATT_HCI_ERR_BASEïƒ

Base value for HCI error status values passed through ATT. Since the values of HCI and ATT error codes overlap, the constant ATT_HCI_ERR_BASE is added to HCI error codes before being passed through ATT. See HCI_SUCCESS for HCI error code values.

Add device to resolving list. When complete the clientâ€™s callback function is called with a DM_PRIV_ADD_DEV_TO_RES_LIST_IND event. The client must wait to receive this event before executing this function again.

Note

This command cannot be used when address resolution is enabled in the Controller and:

  • Advertising (other than periodic advertising) is enabled,

  • Scanning is enabled, or

  • (Extended) Create connection or Create Sync command is outstanding.

Note

If the local or peer IRK associated with the peer Identity Address is all zeros then the Controller will use or accept the local or peer Identity Address respectively.

Note

Parameter â€˜enableLlPrivâ€™ should be set to true when the last device is being added to resolving list to enable address resolution in the Controller.

Parameters:

  • addrType â€“ Peer identity address type.

  • pIdentityAddr â€“ Peer identity address.

  • pPeerIrk â€“ The peerâ€™s identity resolving key.

  • pLocalIrk â€“ The local identity resolving key.

  • enableLlPriv â€“ Set to true to enable address resolution in LL.

  • param â€“ client-defined parameter returned with callback event.

dmSyncId_t DmSyncStart(uint8_t advSid, uint8_t advAddrType, const uint8_t *pAdvAddr, uint16_t skip, uint16_t syncTimeout, uint8_t syncCteType)ïƒ

Synchronize with periodic advertising from the given advertiser, and start receiving periodic advertising packets.

Note: The synchronization filter policy is used to determine whether the periodic advertiser list is used. If the periodic advertiser list is not used, the advertising SID, advertiser address type, and advertiser address parameters specify the periodic advertising device to listen to; otherwise these parameters are ignored.

Parameters:

  • advSid â€“ Advertising SID.

  • advAddrType â€“ Advertiser address type.

  • pAdvAddr â€“ Advertiser address.

  • skip â€“ Number of periodic advertising packets that can be skipped after successful receive.

  • syncTimeout â€“ Synchronization timeout, in the units of 10ms.

  • syncCteType â€“ Whether to only synchronize to periodic advertising with certain types of Constant Tone Extension (0 indicates that the presence or absence of a Constant Tone Extension is irrelevant).

void EattsContinueWriteReq(dmConnId_t connId, uint8_t slot, uint16_t handle, uint8_t status)ïƒ

Send a response to a pending write request. For use with ATT_RSP_PENDING.

Note

When a higher layer returns ATT_RSP_PENDING to an ATT write callback indicating the response status is pending, the higher layer must subsequently call this function with the status of the write request.

Parameters:

  • connId â€“ Connection ID.

  • slot â€“ EATT channel slot ID.

  • handle â€“ Attribute handle.

  • status â€“ Status of the write request.

Parameters:

  • slot â€“ EATT channel slot ID.

HCI Optimization Interface Functions

This is an optimized interface for certain HCI commands that simply read a value. The stack uses these functions rather than their corresponding functions in the command interface. These functions can only be called after the reset sequence has been completed.

l2cCocRegId_t L2cCocRegister(l2cCocCback_t cback, l2cCocReg_t *pReg)ïƒ

Register to use a connection oriented channel, as either a channel acceptor, initiator, or both. If registering as channel acceptor then the PSM is specified. After registering a connection can be established by the client using this registration instance.

Parameters:

  • pReg â€“ Registration parameter structure.

Returns:

Returns:

bool L2cCocEnhancedConnectReq(dmConnId_t connId, l2cCocRegId_t regId, uint16_t psm, uint16_t credits, uint8_t numChan)ïƒ

Send a request to open enhanced credit based channels.

Parameters:

  • connId â€“ DM connection ID.

  • regId â€“ The associated registration instance.

  • psm â€“ The protocol slave multiplexer.

  • credits â€“ The initial number of credits for each CID channel.

  • numChan â€“ The number of channels to create - L2C_MAX_EN_CHAN max.

Returns:

bool L2cCocEnhancedReconfigReq(dmConnId_t connId, uint16_t mtu, uint16_t mps, uint8_t numChan, uint16_t *pChanList)ïƒ

Send a request to reconfigure enhanced credit based channels.

Parameters:

  • connId â€“ DM connection ID.

  • mtu â€“ The maximum transmission unit of each source CID channel.

  • mps â€“ The maximum payload size on each source CID channel.

  • numChan â€“ The number of channels to create (1 to L2C_MAX_EN_CHAN).

  • pChanList â€“ A list of local CID to reconfigure (L2C_MAX_EN_CHAN channels, set unused to 0).

Returns:

false if unable make request, else true.

void L2cCocRegisterAuthorCback(l2cCocAuthorCback_t callback)ïƒ

Register an authorization callback.

Note

If the authorization callback function returns L2C_CONN_FAIL_PEND_AUTHORIZ, then the higher layer shall subsequently call L2cCocAuthorize to authorize the pending request.

Parameters:

callback â€“ The callback function.

void L2cCocAuthorize(dmConnId_t connId, uint16_t psm, bool authorized)ïƒ

Called to authorize a pending enhanced channel requests on a PSM.

Note

This function shall be called to authorize a channel req after L2C_CONN_FAIL_PEND_AUTHORIZ is returned by the authorization callback function (see L2cCocRegisterAuthorCback).

Parameters:

  • connId â€“ Connection ID.

  • psm â€“ The PSM.

  • authorized â€“ true if channel creation is authorized, else false.

void L2cCocAuthenticate(dmConnId_t connId, bool authentic)ïƒ

Called to notify the L2CAP a connection is authentic during a pending enhanced channel requests.

Note

If authenPendSupp was set true in the call to L2cCocChanPendingInit, then this function shall be called by the application after the SMP security procedure. This function will complete a pending enhanced channel request on the given channel.

Parameters:

  • connId â€“ Connection ID.

  • authentic â€“ true if channel creation is authorized, else false.

void L2cCocChanPendingInit(bool authenPendSupp)ïƒ

Initialize enhanced channel request auth pending.

Note

If setting authenPendSupp true, L2cCocAuthenticate shall be called from the application after pairing or encryption is complete to complete channel requests that are pending authentication.

Parameters:

authenPendSupp â€“ true if authentication pending is supported.

Security AES, CMAC and CCM Functions

uint8_t SecAes(uint8_t *pKey, uint8_t *pPlaintext, wsfHandlerId_t handlerId, uint16_t param, uint8_t event)ïƒ

Execute an AES calculation. When the calculation completes, a WSF message will be sent to the specified handler. This function returns a token value that the client can use to match calls to this function with messages.

Parameters:

  • pKey â€“ Pointer to 16 byte key.

  • pPlaintext â€“ Pointer to 16 byte plaintext.

  • handlerId â€“ WSF handler ID.

  • param â€“ Client-defined parameter returned in message.

  • event â€“ Event for clientâ€™s WSF handler.

Returns:

Token value.

uint8_t SecAesRev(uint8_t *pKey, uint8_t *pPlaintext, wsfHandlerId_t handlerId, uint16_t param, uint8_t event)ïƒ

Execute an AES calculation. When the calculation completes, a WSF message will be sent to the specified handler. This function returns a token value that the client can use to match calls to this function with messages. Note this version reverses the key and plaintext bytes.

Parameters:

  • pKey â€“ Pointer to 16 byte key.

  • pPlaintext â€“ Pointer to 16 byte plaintext.

  • handlerId â€“ WSF handler ID.

  • param â€“ Client-defined parameter returned in message.

  • event â€“ Event for clientâ€™s WSF handler.

Returns:

Token value.

bool SecCmac(const uint8_t *pKey, uint8_t *pPlaintext, uint16_t textLen, wsfHandlerId_t handlerId, uint16_t param, uint8_t event)ïƒ

Execute the CMAC algorithm.

Parameters:

  • pKey â€“ Key used in CMAC operation.

  • pPlaintext â€“ Plain text buffer - buffer must persist until secCmacMsg_t callback.

  • textLen â€“ Size of pPlaintext in bytes.

  • handlerId â€“ WSF handler ID for client.

  • param â€“ Optional parameter sent to clientâ€™s WSF handler.

  • event â€“ Event for clientâ€™s WSF handler.
